				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} \mathrm{Da}_\mathrm{vap} =\frac{\tau _\mathrm{vap} }{\tau _\mathrm{chem} }. \end{aligned}$$\end{document}Another dimensionless number that appears in this study is the drying Damköhler number (Dadry)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(\mathrm{Da}_\mathrm{dry})$$\end{document}, which takes into account the effect of the moisture content. Moisture exists in biomass either as bound water, which is held chemically within the cell walls, or as free water, which is stored in the cell cavities. In the drying process, freshly cut or green biomass starts to dry, and initially, the free water evaporates. The fiber saturation point is reached when all the free water is gone, leaving only the bound water within the cell walls [28]. The volatilization resistance of water within biomass particles, which is calculated according to both free and bound water contents, is represented here as4Dadry=τdryτchem.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
