				\begin{document}$$T=T_\mathrm{dry}$$\end{document}, and there is no change in weight of the particles. In the drying subzone, particles’ moisture evaporates in a temperature-increasing process and water vapor is produced. This water vapor diffuses to the previous and the next subzones. In the second heating subzone, the temperature of the particles increases up to volatilization temperature. Finally, in the volatile evaporation subzone, the particles vaporize to yield a gaseous fuel. The gaseous fuel also diffuses to other regions. Because of diffusion phenomena, there is no sharp change in the temperature and quantities of the gaseous fuel. The flame structure of organic dust particles is shown in Fig. 1.Fig. 1
Schematic figure of combustion regions for presented model

To obtain the flame structure, an analytical method is used to solve the governing equations with existing boundary conditions and a matching condition.
